  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contract obligations in FY2026 to date total $456B across all states. Obligations are concentrated: Texas leads with $69.1B, followed by Virginia at $64.2B and California at $38.6B. The top ten states and the District Of Columbia together include Maryland at $22.5B, Arizona at $20.9B, District Of Columbia at $19.2B, Florida at $18.5B, Pennsylvania at $17.8B, Connecticut at $14.5B, and New Mexico at $13.1B. These figures reflect the reported contract obligations to date in FY2026 and highlight which states are receiving the largest shares of federal contracting dollars. The dataset reports total obligations and notes that total award value figures are full contract values, not single-year obligations. For contractors and planners, these figures indicate current allocation of federal contracting activity by state through the FY2026 to date reporting period.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Which states receive the largest shares of federal contract obligations?",
        "body": "Texas receives $69.1B in federal contract obligations, the largest single-state total. Virginia follows with $64.2B and California with $38.6B. The next seven entries are Maryland ($22.5B), Arizona ($20.9B), District Of Columbia ($19.2B), Florida ($18.5B), Pennsylvania ($17.8B), Connecticut ($14.5B), and New Mexico ($13.1B)."
      },
      {
        "heading": "How do total obligations compare across the ranked states?",
        "body": "The ranked entries together sit within the broader FY2026 to date total of $456B in obligations. The top three states—Texas, Virginia, and California—account for the largest individual state totals within that overall figure. The remaining ranked states show smaller but still substantial obligations ranging from $22.5B down to $13.1B."
      }
    ]
  },
